SIMPLE: proscribe
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proscribe
<hw>Pro*scribe"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Proscribed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Proscribing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>proscribere</ets>, <ets>proscriptum</ets>, to write before, to
publish, proscribe; <ets>pro</ets> before + <ets>scribere</ets> to
write. See <er>Scribe</er>. The sense of this word originated in the
Roman practice of writing the names of persons doomed to death, and
posting the list in public.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To doom to
destruction; to put out of the protection of law; to outlaw; to exile;
<as>as, Sylla and Marius <ex>proscribed</ex> each other's
adherents</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Robert Vere, Earl of Oxford, . . . was banished the realm, and
<qex>proscribed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To denounce and condemn; to interdict; to prohibit;
<as>as, the Puritans <ex>proscribed</ex> theaters</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Arian doctrines were <qex>proscribed</qex> and anathematized
in the famous Council of Nice.</q> <rj><qau>Waterland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proscriber</ent>⟦br⟧
